<subSubSection id="C31CD2F88E678046A0E1A579FC563EC2" pageId="4" pageNumber="577" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BB981738E678046A0E1A579FC563EC2" blockId="4.[151,1436,1289,2007]" pageId="4" pageNumber="577">
<emphasis id="B9725D618E678046A0E1A579FE8C3EFE" bold="true" box="[199,334,1910,1935]" pageId="4" pageNumber="577">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name is a reference to the yellow-colored quartz, citrino. The epithet is from the Latin 
<emphasis id="B9725D618E678046A573A578FA593EFF" box="[1365,1435,1911,1934]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="577">citrus,</emphasis>
pure yellow, in reference to the yellow patches on the ventral wings.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31CD2F88E678046A0E1A5B1FC3B3EA6" box="[199,1017,1982,2007]" pageId="4" pageNumber="577" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BB981738E678046A0E1A5B1FC3B3EA6" blockId="4.[151,1436,1289,2007]" box="[199,1017,1982,2007]" pageId="4" pageNumber="577">
<emphasis id="B9725D618E678046A0E1A5B1FEA23EA6" bold="true" box="[199,352,1982,2007]" pageId="4" pageNumber="577">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species is currently known only from its 
<typeStatus id="54BD3FD18E678046A34EA5B0FC5A3EA6" box="[872,920,1983,2007]" pageId="4" pageNumber="577">type</typeStatus>
locality.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="DF79D1FB8E668047A0B1A6FBFE133C5B" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1440355/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="578" startId="5.[151,264,1268,1291]" targetBox="[151,1436,193,1248]" targetPageId="5">
